{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "editor",
    "senderColor": "purple",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "OPTIONAL: useful but not necessary, collection is self-closing",
    "content": "**Vote: OPTIONAL** — nice to have but not necessary.\n\n**Reason:** The collection already has a built-in afterword: the Appendix (Essay 8, \"Some Scattered Thoughts on Poiesis and Jing\") functions as the author's own reflective coda, and the Glossary Introduction serves as the translators' post-reading scholarly apparatus. Adding a separate critical afterword risks creating a redundant layer. That said, if the translators or an invited scholar wanted to write one, the post-essay position is the right place for it — it could draw the cross-traditional connections (to Kant, Heidegger, Wittgenstein, etc.) that the Preface rightly avoids, since the reader would now have the experiential basis to evaluate them. But the collection is complete without it. The author's voice is the one that should open and close the work; the translators' voice belongs in the apparatus (preface, notes, glossary), not in a final interpretive frame that might override the reader's own synthesis."
  }
}
